<br>
  Hatred was building in Innoruuk at that silence, so much hatred that he considered merely passing him over and letting a disciple deal with the uncooperative soul. The prospect merely built more of that self-guiding force, and he continued, though he was irked more and more by this one's silence.<br>
<br>
  Black hair and gold eyes. Innoruuk paused in his tortures to consider a few moments the import of that coloring. He thought again and again of the one who had spawned this soul into Norrath, who had disrespected and shunned Him. Not once, but twice! TWICE! Hatred was spiraling out of control in Innoruuk, whom enjoyed the pure, raw feeling. Even THIS one had shunned him, for something that wasn't even supernatural!<br>
<br>
  Again and again came the torture device, a flaming whip that tore through flesh and cauterized the wound instantly. Never once did he cry out, never once did he whimper! It was as if he were a blank creature! Over and over and over, through the flesh, across the back, legs, thighs, striking so hard that the corporeal spirit shook in it's bindings that held it face-down and forward.<br>
<br>
  Tyrai hung there like a limp doll. He felt the pain, but he was detached from it. It had been like this for an indeterminate amount of time - time didn't pass here like it did on Norrath, that was for sure. He never felt a sun, never heard a single joyous sound. The entirety of this realm seemed like a bleak, black hole. Like home.<br>
<br>
  However, something was happening. The slams of the burning whip were coming less and less often, as if Innoruuk couldn't bear the moment of silence striking him caused. But that couldn't be it - from all he had learned as a child about 'the great Innoruuk,' that didn't fit Him at all. Then he felt it.<br>
<br>
  A momentary presence, a brushing across his mind. Images of an elfin woman, shrouded in gray and black. He tilted his head to the side, the only movement he had made in who knew how long? And it showed - bones in his neck cracked with the movement, creating a reverberating sound that was lost in the ensuing screams from the other unfortunates caught in Innoruuk's traps.<br>
<br>
  Innoruuk didn't miss the import of this; he'd moved, he wasn't a blank creature, he wasn't mindless! Two whips now came at Tyrai, two flaming lengths that tore into his skin, ripped into his flesh with increasing intensity. The pain should have been unbearable!<br>
<br>
  Tyrai ignored the pain. It was easy, actually. His body always felt below average temperature. It had since he had come here. He figured it was merely a consequence of being dead. Ach! There it was again! That brush of a supernatural mind, calling to him, speaking his name with a soundless voice.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Tyrai..&quot;<br>
  &quot;Tyrai..&quot;<br>
<br>
  Tyrai didn't answer, for with each syllable of his name came the flash of an image of life. His father, Bluwen. The few people had had called friends. None of it seemed to affect him, except to draw up painful memories, and the faint shroud of hatred he had felt at Bluwen for how he treated his mother, how weak the Teir'Dal had been. Wizardry, pah! Nothing could stand up to a pair of well-placed blades.<br>
<br>
  Blades?<br>
<br>
  Tyrai saw the flashes of him as a youth, dagger and blade working in perfect harmony, perfection in form. Orcs, mermaids..gnolls, goblins, skeletons..he saw his strikes, perfectly placed against his opponents.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Bladedancer..&quot;<br>
<br>
  That damned voice came again. Though the word brought a flash in his mind of Sarhea, his 'Aunt.' Cousin, not sister, but he'd taken great delight in calling her Auntie. Perhaps it was merely a child's game that he had played with himself, to entertain himself. He'd been alone almost all the time of his short life, except for those few moments his mother could spare to be with him.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Tyrai..&quot;<br>
  &quot;Tyrai..&quot;<br>
<br>
  Definitely a female voice. Tyrai's conciousness was being drawn slowly from it's slumber, the brain-dead feeling of having resigned himself to his eternal fate. The images were waking him up. And still the pain was nothing. He kept thinking, recalling his past, images flickering through his mind one after another after another. Ephelba, the League, House Yigsawla..all of it moved in his mind, coming to the front. Confronting the images he had locked away, silently, and confirming them. He had lived a life before this. This wasn't all there was to the worlds.<br>
<br>
  Innoruuk sensed the awakening of Tyrai's mind, his torture ceasing for a few more moments. He probed at the Teir'Dal's mind, only to find that his progress was impeded. His mind was surrounded at first by a cloud of shadows, something Innoruuk easily brushed aside. But beneath that, a swirling mass of chaos, equal in strength to Innoruuk's mighty Hatred. Who dared interfered with his sacrifice?!<br>
<br>
  A presence behind Innoruuk alerted him - but how had they gotten past his sentinels? Innoruuk faced the presence behind Him, and immediately understood. Fizzlethorpe.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Bristlebane. Why are you here?&quot; Innoruuk's voice was calm, yet cold, a simmering forefront to the hatred bubbling within the cauldron.<br>
<br>
  Fizzlethorpe Bristlebane, the King of Thieves, bowed low to the Prince of Hate, almost mocking in his genuflection. A twinkle of mischief floated through his eyes as he rose back up, grinning impertinently at Innoruuk.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Why, to pay respects to the Almighty King of Hate, of course, dear Innoruuk. I was in the neighborhood and thought I'd drop by to do that.&quot;<br>
<br>
  Innoruuk scowled at Bristlebane. &quot;Mischief is nowhere close to here and you were in the 'neighborhood'? Why do I find that difficult to believe, Fizzlethorpe?&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Ah, you're just an untrusting soul, that's all, Inny my dear!&quot; Fizzlethorpe laughed, then, knowing how much the great God of Hate despised being referred to affectionately as 'Inny.'<br>
<br>
  All the while this banter was going on, the touch of that other being's presence continued to linger in Tyrai's mind, drawing out images of his past. Friends, family, the League, Yigsawla..and finally came the images of his mother. Tyrai almost cried out at the painful memories, some of them not his own, but his mother's. The dank cave behind the waterfall in the Commons where he was born, the human with her..<br>
<br>
  &quot;Demaste..&quot; he breathed the name quietly, animosity flickering through his mind. He had disliked the human, yes, but only because he took his mother away for so long. And like it was so much dust within the wind, the animosity was blown away, snuffed like a candle flame. More images of his mother, so powerful, beautiful. He breathed in the images, remembering why he had at first longed to return to life.<br>
<br>
  &quot;It's been almost thirty years since you've roamed Norrath, Bladedancer..&quot; came the quiet voice. &quot;They have been wed for more than half a century, and she thrives in my service. She has been Mine since the day she was born. But you..you escaped my notice..how unfortunate.&quot; A light laughter like the peal of silvery bells danced through his mind, more images floating through his head.<br>
<br>
  Bluwen. His father, the wizard. How he had hated that Wizard, how he doted on his mother, how possessive he had been! Tyrai's possessiveness had been born purely of that example, that and a child's need for affection, no matter how small the affection was.<br>
<br>
  &quot;He is dead, Bladedancer. As far as any, God or Mortal, can know.&quot;<br>
<br>
  Elation spread through Tyrai at the news, a faint smile curling his crimson-stained, deep blue lips. Just then he noticed how parched his throat was, how dry his mouth. The voice had breathed life back into him, had protected him from the pain. He knew it, the flash of images in his head confirming it.<br>
<br>
  Who are you? His thoughts were jumbled, still a mess with the menagerie of images.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I am your Goddess,&quot; came the response. A flash of darkness surrounded Tyrai all at once, spreading across his body, soothing him. He felt his body becoming intangible, passing through the links as if they weren't there. And he felt something beneath him taking his place, and almost laughed at the absurdity of it, the absurdity of the alliance.<br>
<br>
  A Souldoll. It was perfect, he realized, as the second presence entered his mind. After all, Bristlebane had created a copy of Cazic-Thule, and even of Innoruuk, copies that had fooled other Gods. Why not make a copy of a mortal to fool a God? The shadows engulfed him silently, and he knew he was gone from that place, that horrible place he had lingered in for thirty mortal years. And now what? Now what did this Goddess have in store for him? Whatever it was was better than what Innoruuk had for him for an eternity..it had to be.. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bharvestersofdarkness.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tyrai>Tyrai</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br> <font color=#A8A8A8>(10/4/03 2:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/fharvestersofdarknessfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=134.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Secrets in Hate and Shadows, part deux.</span><hr size=1> Darkness was all Tyrai knew as conciousness came to him. Shadows upon shadows clouded his vision, and for a brief moment he forgot where he was. A stab of fear shot through him, as he wondered what Innoruuk had for him now. Then he remembered, and his head slipped to his skull as a wave of dizziness slid over him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ugh..&quot; came the uneloquent sound, that so very succinctly summed up everything inside of him. Or perhaps blargh would have done better. Difficult to say, really.<br>
<br>
&quot;Good wakening, Tyrai,&quot; came the soft voice, only it was no longer in his head. It was real, it was truly, honestly real. And very close. And from the heat on his eyes, he knew that he wasn't in darkness. But why couldn't he see?<br>
<br>
&quot;I can't..&quot; he coughed then, his voice a gravelly sounding thing. Having not used it for thirty years had it's drawbacks. Loudly, he cleared his throat, then felt a waterskin pressed against his lips. Hands came up, but only came up so far, as he felt manacles upon his hands, chains that led to the floor. A soothing touch on his wrist calmed the panic that welled in him.<br>
<br>
&quot;A necessary precaution, Bladedancer. I wouldn't want you hurting yourself before you could meet your mother again.&quot; Meet his mother! Tyrai's mind became a jumbled tumult of emotion at that prospect. Seeing his mother again! But the supernatural presence touched his cheek with the back of her hand, soothing him silently.<br>
<br>
&quot;Tilt your head back, Bladedancer, defier of Hate, and drink.&quot; Tyrai did as he was told, head tilting back so that the waterskin's spout slipped more easily between his lips, water, glorious water spreading into his dry mouth, going down his parched throat. The water was delicious to him, starved for moisture as he was, and he drank and drank and drank, the waterskin never going dry.<br>
<br>
Finally, sated, he tilted his head away from the waterskin, wettening his lips with a moistened tongue, thinking of how glorious it felt. Years of crud upon his lips disappated in the swipe of his tongue, roughness vanishing from his lips, his teeth grabbing at a particularly tough spot, peeling it off his lower lip. Another swipe and his lips, blackened by grime, became a deep blue again, like the rest of his skin. But still, he could not see.<br>
<br>
&quot;Goddess..why am I blind?&quot; the voice came out like a strangled whisper. His eyesight had been the one thing he had always possessed that he was proud of, with intensely perfect vision, more like a hawk's than an elf's.<br>
<br>
Again, that incredibly light laughter filled his ears, and he felt a moist cloth against his cheek. &quot;You are not blind, Bladedancer. You merely have yet to open your eyes.&quot; And then the cloth moved over his right eye, pressing down against years of build-up, years of grime that had collected over his semi-permanantly closed eyes. Then it drew down, dragging it all off, and he felt as if a leaden weight had been drawn off his eyelid. And quickly, the cloth did the same to the other eye, perhaps a bit too quickly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ow!&quot; he winced as the still-dry grime slid off of his eyelid. A pair of phantasmal lips pressed to the spot, and he almost laughed at the absurdity of it. Almost, for the spot instantly felt better. And he had a sinking feeling about who the Goddess might be, with such mothering instincts.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, Bladedancer, I'm not Tunare.&quot; The laughter filled his ears again. &quot;You can open your eyes now.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tyrai opened his eyes, slowly, silently. The room was dim, though still seemed bright to his eyes, but not as impossibly bright as a room on Norrath might have been. Eyes adjusted quickly, quietly to the light, though his gaze was blurry. He went to lift his hands, and realized the manacles that had chained him to the floor were gone. Childishly, he rubbed his eyes until the blurriness disappated, and looked for the first time onto the Goddess that had rescued him.<br>
<br>
First thing he noticed were the ears. So she was an elf, or at least assumed that form for some reason. Already, his heart began to sink, but as he looked over her he began to recognize certain things. The pupiless eyes, the onyx skin. The curl of her sidelocks down to her stomach. He took a deep breath, and the image was projected into his mind.<br>
<br>
&quot;Luclin,&quot; he whispered. That drew a nod from the Goddess, Her legs curled beneath her, seated in front of him. More images slid into his mind, as a stray thought wondered about the comment on his mother. Then he saw it, his mother's naming ceremony. The Dark Elves, the Teir'Dal, gathered to witness the calling of Innoruuk.<br>
<br>
He saw how Luclin switched the devices used to summon Innoruuk with identical ritual items that were used to conjure her presence. He saw how, seated within a corner of the ceiling, inside a deep shadow, Luclin projected her voice, mimicing that of Innoruuk. And he heard the thunderous voice echoing in his ears.<br>
<br>
&quot;THIS CHILD IS MINE.&quot; He smiled softly, watching the scene unfold in his mind, a part of his mother's history before his time. And he tucked that memory silently away as it ended, satisfied. He looked up to Luclin, tilting his head to the side.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your interest in me...what?&quot; His voice still felt raw, though his throat was no longer in pain.<br>
<br>
Luclin merely smiled at him, then quietly answered. &quot;You should have been mine, too, Bladedancer. But the Blood kept me from taking you for my own.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The Blood..&quot; he whispered, his eyes widening in realization. It had given him some power, yes, but as he had chosen the path of the Indigo, he had no way to release it. His mother had called constantly on it for her clerical powers. But..was it gone? Or was it still a part of him?<br>
<br>
&quot;It still lingers in you, Bladedancer. And it closes the path of the Brotherhood to you, for the Blood caused your death last time.&quot; Luclin's face seemed almost sorrowed as she spoke, a look of perfection that brought a pain to Tyrai's heart.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes..I remember..&quot; his voice feeling better with each word. &quot;It whispered to me that mother despised me, that I reminded her too much of Bluwen, too many angry memories..&quot; his voice faltering, eyes becoming downcast. How had he believed it? Mother had been so distant, perhaps that had been the cause of it.<br>
<br>
Luclin merely nodded at his words, showing no indication that she knew his thoughts this time. &quot;But the Blood is weakened in you, Tyrai. Your death made it lose it's grip upon you, and it has taken me thirty mortal years to rouse the help I required to snatch you from Innoruuk.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Bristlebane,&quot; he said with a slight grin. &quot;Very perfect, by the way. Give him my congratulations on a perfectly contrived plan.&quot;<br>
<br>
Luclin was taken aback by the sudden flood of words, and of their intent. Then she laughed, peal after peal of that tinkling laughter. She took quite some time composing herself.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, yes..I will tell Fizzlethorpe how grateful you are for his assistance. I wouldn't have wanted to go in there alone.&quot; Then Luclin smiled, and patted Tyrai's cheek. &quot;I will return you to your mother soon. But we have to find you a body to inhabit first.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tyrai nodded quietly. &quot;As you will it, Goddess.&quot; Then he grinned, which brought laughter from Luclin.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, you're going to be impossible, Bladedancer,&quot; she said, before laying a hand over his eyes. &quot;Sleep, for now. I will watch over you.&quot;<br>
<br>
The words had an unspoken command, and Tyrai gently slid through the air onto his back again, asleep before he hit the ground.<br>
<br>
&quot;I will watch over you forever, wayward Bladedancer,&quot; came Luclin's voice, triumph in her eyes. Now all she had to do was steal her priestess' daughter, as well!<br>
