<br>
  &quot;Makes me wonder how laughter would feel,&quot; he murmured, a grin spreading across his deep blue lips. His body felt somewhat weak, though he had retained most of the hardiness he'd had in life. All that Brotherhood training, becoming better than the Dreadguard, had paid off. Tyrai moved up onto his feet silently, walking over to a large bay window in the wall directly across from where he'd been sleeping.<br>
<br>
  Beyond the low light of the room, he saw..nothing. That is to say, he saw the Demi-Plane of Shadows, the only tangible thing within it the building he was in. Below he saw nothing but gentle darkness that swayed with a silent rythym within the plane. Nothing could be more perfect, this silence, this serenity. A smile curled his lips, as he looked silently away from the window.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Yes, it is peaceful here.&quot; Luclin had returned, gazing quietly at the Teir'Dal. &quot;But you have to leave soon, my new disciple.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Why?&quot; Tyrai asked, though he felt shame at asking the question. He knew he couldn't stay here an eternity - he had yet to live his mortal life out. Luclin merely nodded at him, then gestured silently at the window.<br>
<br>
  Tyrai turned, and the window formed, shaping silently into a portal of unimaginable darkness. A pulsing light appeared in the center of the portal, flowing silently outwards. The portal turned swiftly into a viewing glass, and he saw, through it, the image of a young Teir'Dal, a bit older than he had been when he had died.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I have chosen a mortal form for you, Tyrai.&quot; Luclin was at his side, her voice at his ear. He studied the figure through the portal, watching him talk, move, cast. He saw the Necromantic spells, and a light flickered in his eyes, a grin on his lips. Something in the magic appealed to him. Perhaps it was Luclin's gentle insistence upon his mind, but more than not, it was the way everything seemed so very effective, deadly so.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I will go then, my Lady of Shadows,&quot; Tyrai spoke, his voice flowing easily now, the timbre of adulthood replacing the squeaks of youth. He turned to look at Luclin, knowing that most mortals never got to see their worship face to face. He was fortunate, yes, but he knew the real value of this. The Mistress of Shadows merely nodded, gesturing silently towards the portal, which swirled back into a seamless void.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Wait until I tell you, then enter the portal. Force the other soul out and take the body for your own. I do not know what will happen after that, Bladedancer, but this is how you will enter back into life.&quot; Luclin grinned softly at his confused expression, touching his cheek. &quot;I know you will be able to do this. You are stronger than he, by far.&quot; Tyrai nodded, then looked to the portal, and waited..<br>
<br>
  Kineu Do'Umbra, a young Necromancer in his late teens, moved swiftly through the halls of Neriak. He was a devout of Innoruuk, a Dark Priest of the Dead, and used his Hatred to fuel his magics. And he was good, perhaps one of the strongest upcoming Necromancers in all of Neriak.<br>
<br>
  But today, he wasn't thinking that. He was wandering the dark recesses of Neriak, the hidden tunnels behind the fall. An alluring voice had drawn him here, promising him power, a seat at Innoruuk's side. Yet he found nothing here, but kept looking. And as he reached the end, he heard the voice again, turning him around.<br>
<br>
  What he saw was a Royal Teir'Dal, or at least that is what she seemed like. Her skin was as dark as the night, without the faintest touch of blue to it, and her eyes pupiless. Almost immediately he was taken with the strange beauty. She spoke without words to him, the promises from before silently filling his mind. He didn't notice the soul approaching him until it was too late.<br>
<br>
  Kineu Do'Umbra was in pain. His back arched as he felt something enter him, something supernatural. He fought with his body and mind, attacking the soul that was entering his body with a savage possessiveness. He twisted, turned, and screamed, calling forth Innoruuk's name, trying to save himself from the darkness that descended upon him, shrouding him in shadows.<br>
<br>
  All at once, however, the battle was ended. Kineu Do'Umbra's soul was dismissed from the body he had possessed, and Tyrai had entered it. The young Necromancer was gone, returned to the Cauldron, and in his place was Tyrai.<br>
<br>
  &quot;The body is yours, Bladedancer,&quot; whispered Luclin. And then she noticed the pain etched into Tyrai's face.<br>
<br>
  As Tyrai had entered the body, so had the Blood that possessed his spirit. And the Blood did not like this body's shape, or form. Muscles rippled through the deep blue skin, restoring what had been the shape of Tyrai's body, the Warrior, before he had died. Slim muscles that relied more on speed and grace than sheer force. Also, the stark white hair that had been the Necromancer's pride was suddenly darkened to black, growing from the short-cropped end down to his shoulders. Eyes of pearlescent blue were suddenly gold, luminous and glowing as the Blood forced it's way through the body, forcing these changes.<br>
<br>
  Through it all, Tyrai bore the pain with the silent stoicism he had taken Innoruuk's beatings with. And when it was finished, he silently looked down upon his leather-clad body, a grin spreading across his lips. He looked to Luclin, and nodded at her.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Now I shall find Kerridwynn D'Veldrin, and inquire of my mother's whereabouts.&quot; Luclin looked slightly surprised at the change in Tyrai, but she didn't say anything about it. Instead, she spoke merely of his future.<br>
<br>
  &quot;She is Kerridwynn Spellbender now, and strife rules her house for the time being. Wait some time before making yourself known to your mother and her husband, and their daughter.&quot;<br>
<br>
  It was Tyrai's turn to look surprised, as she spoke that final word. &quot;I have..a sister?&quot; he whispered, blinking once, twice, three times. Then he smiled, and nodded. &quot;It is as it should be, then. What is her name, Mistress?&quot; He looked imploringly at the Goddess, whom indulged him.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Kyimera Spellbender, a Knight of Darkness.&quot; Tyrai nodded silently, taking this all in. And then, suddenly, he realized he wasn't breathing, and his lungs were screaming for air. He took a breath, and a hand slid to his head, suddenly dizzy with the sensation of breathing again. Everything was so crisp and clear to his newly restored senses! And his vision, oh, what a delight it was to see things unclouded by Planesight, that accursed shadowing that had blurred his vision for thirty years. And the youth of this form, oh! He wagered that, despite the difference in years, the youth had brought him somewhere to an age around twenty-five years.<br>
<br>
  And the magic that flowed in him, the power he had stolen from it's rightful owner; that was his too, this necromantic strength. He laughed softly, looking around the dank caves, then back to Luclin, nodding towards her. &quot;It shall be as you say, Mistress, but I will look in on my mother.&quot; Luclin merely nodded, then began to fade away, back into her home plane.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Be well, my new Disciple, my..Bonedancer.&quot; Luclin laughed, that silvery peal echoing across the cave walls as she faded away, silently leaving Tyrai to himself and his new strength. Tyrai looked down at his hands, and smiled softly.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Alive..&quot; he breathed, then quickly rushed from the caves, to explore.. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bharvestersofdarkness.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tyrai>Tyrai</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br> <font color=#A8A8A8>(10/6/03 7:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/fharvestersofdarknessfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=134.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Secrets in Hate and Shadows, part quatre.</span><hr size=1> Tyrai quietly looked at his reflection in the still pool of the chamber deep beneath Neriak, regarding the sight that stared back at him. His golden eyes seemed more sinister due to the smattering of crimson stain across his eyelids, barely tinging his dark blue skin, creating a mere highlight across his face.<br>
<br>
His lips, too, were changed, black paint across them, staining them to a deep onyx. His lips pressed together for a brief instant, before his tongue slipped out to moisten his lips. The paint creased down into the folds of his lips, the smooth, polished onyx look vanishing.<br>
<br>
Down his gaze went, to his hands, a sanguine coloring across his trimmed fingernails, standing out against his skin. And, too, he considered the leathers he wore, thinking them quite fitting.<br>
<br>
&quot;Deep shadows and brilliant highlights..could the Goddess be any better represented?&quot; Even his voice seemed like a silken shadow, matured from the squeak of his teens to a melodic, almost hypnotic deep roll. He couldn't even recognize himself in the reflection.<br>
<br>
&quot;What does Mother see now in her reflection, though, I wonder..&quot; he whispered to himself, thinking how he had seen her in Nektulos. The silver lines down her cheeks, molten silver cooled in wounds. From the brief touches on her mind, he knew what they represented, why she had done it.<br>
<br>
&quot;Soon I'll understand nothing of her,&quot; he said with a chuckle. &quot;Twentieth circle comes soon, and this glorious, stolen power from the Goddess will fade. Her protection will end.&quot; He had so many things to consider upon reaching the twentieth circle, but there was one thing that he did not need to consider. How he would present himself to his mother, there in the Harvester's Hall. Nothing dramatic, mere simplicity.<br>
<br>
Tyrai looked quietly to the glowing skull he had taken from a skeleton's body, and thought again of the brittle iksar skull sitting on his mother's mantle. He spoke quietly, reaching out to run his fingers over the skull's smooth brow.<br>
<br>
&quot;This will outdo the skull my sister gave to her. Or perhaps it will merely equal, or pale in comparison to my return.&quot; His melodic voice was musing, seeming to lull himself into a trance, falling into himself to think.<br>
<br>
He had made contact with his half-sister, Kyimera, tonight. She was strong already, stronger than he was with his current experience. But he wondered, silently, how her skill with the blade she carried would have matched his speed with his dagger and blade. Then, he laughed.<br>
<br>
&quot;I haven't even met her and already I'm competing.&quot; His fingers continued to stroke the glowing iksar skull's brow, pondering. Was he still possessive of her? He didn't know. He'd have to meet her full on before he could decide. How quickly the jealousy would rise the moment she turned to someone else. Again, a laugh slipped from between those painted black lips, and he shook his head.<br>
<br>
&quot;That got me dead in the first place and in that horrid plane..&quot; he whispered. And then, he wondered, how many of his mother's family worshipped the Father, and how many would be offended by his escape from His clutches. Perhaps he should show himself before his twentieth season, so that Luclin could shield him..<br>
<br>
&quot;No!&quot; The word shot from his lips like an arrow, an arrow that curved and bit into him, piercing him to his soul. &quot;I was never a coward, never ashamed of what I was, who I was. Why begin now?&quot; The words came freely, as if from outside himself, but he wholeheartedly agreed with them. It would wait until his twentieth circle, the twentieth blade, the twentieth shadow.<br>
<br>
A bone chip came into his hand, and then another. Turning, he spread the chips of bone in his hand, his digits working as gracefully as a rogue's on a lockpick, rolling the chips over his finger, in between each finger. They met in the middle, 'twixt the second and third finger, then continued past each other. And the direction reversed as they reached the next space, bringing them back together between his fingers.<br>
<br>
Down went the bonechips then, shadows coalescing about them. Shades rising in response to his call, forming the bones of a spindly creature, rising from the dispersing chips of bone. A shadowed skeleton stood before him, intelligence in it's green glowing eyes that pulsed with his magic, only faintly necromantic in nature.<br>
<br>
&quot;They call the Necromancers of Queen Crysthanos Thex 'Bonedancers.' It would be rude of me to take their name, would it not?&quot; Already, his mind was twisting about the idea, engulfing it with enthusiasm. He had never intended to use that title for himself; any others seemed ridiculous, but for one.<br>
<br>
The shadowed skeleton moved to him, laying it's hand on his shoulder. Tyrai looked up and grinned, seeing the reflection of Luclin within the pulsating eyes, nodding at the unspoken approval.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shadowdancer, then,&quot; he murmured, a surge of elation passing through him as he spoke the name. Whether it was his, or Luclin's, or both, he was not sure. But he knew that She was pleased by the title he took. He racked his brain silently, trying to remember enough of the language his mother had spoken with great fervor when he'd been young to construct a proper title from it.<br>
<br>
&quot;D'Veldrin was her surname, and would have been mine, eventually,&quot; he said quietly. &quot;Of Shadows. It seems appropriate, yet inappropriate.&quot; Why bother with that language, that horrible language all spoke? <br>
<br>
&quot;Later, after I meet Mother. I will decide then.&quot; He nodded to himself, and checked his makeup one more time in the reflection of the pool. He was going to visit the Necropolis, despite it having been ravaged, and he was going to listen in shadows. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bharvestersofdarkness.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tyrai>Tyrai</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br> <font color=#A8A8A8>(10/6/03 9:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/fharvestersofdarknessfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=134.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Secrets in Hate and Shadows, part finir.</span><hr size=1> Tyrai flicked his hand smoothly towards the recondite, luring it towards him with a blast of shadows that entangled it's legs, curling about it's body and began to eat away at the skin. In short order, the regular heartbeat was irregulated, and the temperature of it's body rose several degrees, due to the blood that began to simmer in the veins.<br>
<br>
The power of these spells was undeniable. And he was only a few seasons into it! A blast of necromantic magic ripped life from the recondite as it swung at Tyrai, instantly healing the wound that the fist had caused without so much as a bruise. The shadowed skeleton that accompanied him suddenly flew into action, the shade releasing a torrent of blows upon the recondite, pulsating green eyes gleaming with madness.<br>
<br>
Tyrai stood there, deflecting blows with his short-handled scythe, occasionally raising the Writ in his other hand to fend off a quickened blow. His muscles were sluggish, however, not fully recovered from returning to life, and blows got through his defense.<br>
<br>
A final blast of Necromantic magic ended the pain, however, rending the life from the recondite and restoring Tyrai's skin to an unmarred state.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, he felt the shadows about him buckling. The defense that Luclin had given him was failing, that defense that had rendered him nigh a demi-god. Now the twentieth circle had descended upon him, and Luclin was taking the strength back.<br>
<br>
Tyrai exhaled slowly as the shadows pulled away from him, feeling suddenly..alive. He was completely tangible now, fully into the material plane. No longer could he shadow his mother or the Harvesters. He had to rely solely upon his own power now.<br>
<br>
&quot;Good,&quot; he murmured, as the thought slipped through his mind. &quot;I never was much one who needed assistance. Thank you, nontheless, Goddess.&quot; He was talking, of course, to Luclin, whom he knew could hear him, his every thought, if she listened.<br>
<br>
Tyrai tested the weight of the scythe now that his muscles weren't filled by the shadow's power. It still weighed almost nothing, and his skill was undiminished. So that had been him, it seemed. His old training was coming back to him. He knew that one power still remained, though. The ability to disperse his corporeal form to the shadows. But without Luclin's assistance, it would take him a good deal of time to regather it into a physical presence.<br>
<br>
